04289nam a22005055i 9780226828176DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226828176  a(DE-B1597)658671  a(OCoLC)1381712417  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aHM571b.D766 2024 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a301.0722231 aDromi, Shai M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMoral Minefields :bHow Sociologists Debate Good Science /cShai M. Dromi, Samuel D. Stabler. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (240 p.) :b4 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface: Eternity in Cincinnati -- tIntroduction: Rules of the road -- t1: Navigating in a minefield -- t2: Academic no- go zones -- t3: Moral highways and byways -- t4: Chartered trips -- tConclusion: on moral grounds -- tAfterword: researching the good in research justifications -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn analysis of the effects of moral debates on sociological research. Few academic disciplines are as contentious as sociology. Sociologists routinely turn on their peers with fierce criticisms not only of their empirical rigor and theoretical clarity but of their character as well. Yet despite the controversy, scholars manage to engage in thorny debates without being censured. How? In Moral Minefields, Shai M. Dromi and Samuel D. Stabler consider five recent controversial topics in sociology—race and genetics, secularization theory, methodological nationalism, the culture of poverty, and parenting practices—to reveal how moral debates affect the field. Sociologists, they show, tend to respond to moral criticism of scholarly work in one of three ways. While some accept and endorse the criticism, others work out new ways to address these topics that can transcend the criticism, while still others build on the debates to form new, more morally acceptable research. Moral Minefields addresses one of the most prominent questions in contemporary sociological theory: how can sociology contribute to the development of a virtuous society? Rather than suggesting that sociologists adopt a clear paradigm that can guide their research toward neatly defined moral aims, Dromi and Stabler argue that sociologists already largely possess and employ the repertoires to address questions of moral virtue in their research. The conversation thus is moved away from attempts to theorize the moral goods sociologists should support and toward questions about how sociologists manage the plurality of moral positions that present themselves in their studies. Moral diversity within sociology, they show, fosters disciplinary progress.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aSocial sciences and ethics. 0aSociologyxResearchxMoral and ethical aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  asociology, pragmatism, race, scientific controversy, morality, repertoires, gender, religion, national identity, scientific change.1 aStabler, Samuel D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079732940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226828176423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226828176/original  a978-3-11-079732-9  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles